    "Management": {
      "text": "Increasing HR decreases QT interval\nMagnesium sulfate\n- decreases calcium influx\n1-2gm IV over 1-2 min, repeat in 5-15min; then 1-2gm/hr (3-10mg/min) drip\nDanger of\nhypermagnesemia\n→ depressed neuromuscular function and respiratory drive, so monitor closely\nSupplement with K+\nIsoproterenol\n- Increases HR / AV conduction\n2-8 mcg/min\nTarget HR > 90 bpm\nOverdrive Pacing\n- Atrial > Ventricular pacing\nGoal HR 90-120\nNote: Not a treatment for TdP, but useful in maintaining sinus rhythm\nDefibrillation\n/\nsynchronized cardioversion\n- Patient in extremis\nAVOID\namiodarone and procainamide, which may worsen prolonged QT\nLidocaine\n(a class Ib antiarrhythmic drug) shortens the QT interval and may be effective especially for drug-induced torsades de pointes\nLidocaine\n1 mg/kg bolus, followed by 0.5-4 mg/min, titrated to rhythm response\n[1]\nInpatient may monitor plasma lidocaine levels, with goal < 6 mcg/mL",
